segments.text: Okay, it's going now.
That was terrific.
To start at the lowest level was just about the most fun you could have.
Maybe some girl will like you at the end of the night.
Of course, there's always some guy that takes a fancy to her, so he wants to beat you up, so you get to practice fighting at the same time.
That was interesting.
That was always the way it was.
I don't care
Somebody comes and says, let's leave at once.
I say, yeah, yeah, let's go.
And then all of a sudden, some clowns come skulking up.
Hey, man, I like her.
I say, well, that's the brakes, bubba.
No, it ain't neither.
So you practice all that stuff.
But if you're a delinquent to begin with, you don't care.
I didn't care.
You win, you lose.
So that was the only reason I'm talking about that.
That's why I decided I didn't really feel sorry for struggling musicians that I've encountered on tour.
So you look at the Rock and Roll Pyramid, all the money is up at the top.
Thousands and millions of people are languishing, making no money whatsoever, or $5 a night.
As long as they don't fancy that they're embarked on some kind of big career trip, that's fine.
If you can enjoy the level you're at, it's a very great thing.
What could be more fun than being in the band?
I think it's great.
Am I jealous that Barry Manilow makes all this money?
No, but I think it's ridiculous.
Okay.
Where do you think the velvet's fed into, though?
musical scene in the 60s?
Or do you think they were just more or less remembered?
Well, we didn't really.
We seemed to fit a whole lot better into the late 70s and 80s.
We were sort of minimalist and direct.
All we did is we were kind of heavy metal sometimes and
Lyrically, we're kind of weird.
We never did fit into the mainstream, obviously.
We sold trillions of records.
But you could hear where we came from.
You could hear this R&B in there.
You really can in the early stuff.
I don't deceive myself.
Somebody just gave me a tape of a group in the Netherlands doing Run, Run, Run and Sunday Morning.
In Run, Run, Run, they
They correctly isolate the essential R&B riff in it, and then in fact emphasize it on the chorus.
Run, run, run, take a drag or two, that thing.
They use a walking bass line, which it would really have if it were done by Bobby Blue Bland or somebody.
They really picked up on it as an R&B
inspired thing, and just emphasized it.
So there's always this sort of thing.
European Sun, we had, frequently we had different titles for the songs.
European Sun, we used to talk, we used to refer to as John Lee Hooker, because it has an old John Lee Hooker riff buried under there someplace.
John Lee Hooker was great.
He's a sad case, back to
I was thinking about the perils of folk singing and selling out.
A lot of these black R&B guys put down their steel strings and got these old gut string guitars and started playing for little white kids.
This was horrible.
John Lee Hooker being one of them started popping up in coffee houses as sort of a black folk singer.
I'd be out there.
I heard him once do that.
I said, no, no, no.
He had all these old John Lee Hooker records where he had bands.
Boy, they were great, great things.
But who could blame him?
He was signed on for life.
I wasn't.
I was just some white kid.
While I liked to play, I liked to play.
I still like to play.
It's just very...
I don't want to go into it on this thing.
Why does that count?
I did have a little experiment here in Austin, 77 to 79, and ended unhappily.
All I wanted to do was be a roadhouse band, fabulously successful.
I'm not kidding.
We set house records and we invented the Continental Club and all that sort of thing.
We're fondly remembered.
And it collapsed because of ambition.
All these people

secretly they're friends of mine before we saw the play together secretly thought that um if i did it for a while immediately i'd want to start writing again and calling people in new york and going on tour and making records and like i said then they got furious so it's okay for you because you already did it i said well yeah you're right so maybe you want to find somebody else who really wants to do it and go do it so that brought all that down it was unfortunate
I was here once this summer, and I saw a flyer for a band, Femme Fatale.
Oh, Femme Fatale.
Yeah.
I don't know.
It's a stock phrase.
I wonder if they play this song.
But you see an influence that the Velvets had on some later stuff.
The punk movement, heavy metal, and some of the new wave, like I believe Rick Ocasek of the Cars has mentioned the Velvets as a primary influence.
Yeah.
Well, his drummer came by way of the Modern Lovers.
Jonathan Richmond was like our protege from the time he was 14 years old.
Hung around with us and all that sort of thing.
Yeah, that's all kind of nice.
See, the material is always there.
It hasn't been overplayed on the radio.
In fact, it hasn't been played there at all.
It was banned from the radio, and even advertising for it was banned.
So it's very easy to make those kind of exciting personal discoveries.
You want to hear something that really hasn't been played to death, it's our old stuff.
We did sell enough records, though, we really did.
Compared to the cars, we haven't.
But we did okay.
Still doing okay royalty-wise.
So I don't feel bad about that.
But I wasn't in it for a business I don't know.
If you're interested in business, go work for your uncle in the hardware store.
Same kind of thing.
But it is flattering to be an influence.
Flattering, but not profitable.
But what endures and what doesn't?
Money doesn't.
I would rather be well thought of than be some schmuck with a whole lot of money that everybody despises.
A category which
includes many of my contemporaries.
Did you see the Volvets as any influence on society at the time, or just an extension of the avant-garde and beatnik society in New York at the time?
We're not an influence because it was a closed society from the beginning.
You couldn't join because you couldn't get in.
in a kind of, it was not anything that was marketable or exploitable.
We had kind of fashion connections, you know, through paraphernalia and Betsy Johnson.
But Betsy talks in the biography about how the impression was that everybody is on our wavelength and doing all these crazy things, where in fact very few people were, numerically.
What is the high glamour crowd doing right this minute?
Well, I'm not sure.
I was just in New York.
It's not a whole lot of... Billy Idol looks like all the rest of the people who are trying to look like Billy Idol.
So there's nothing particularly distinctive about the way we dressed.
We were slobby.
By turns.
We had real good clothes at other times.
Betsy made clothes for us.
We certainly bought enough of them.
We never wore them.
I had great stuff.
I used to lose most of it.
I remember just wearing T-shirts and jeans.
We didn't try to influence anything.
There were clothing stores called the Velvet Underground.
There was a chain.
It may still be
But that wasn't based on anything that we wore in particular.
The girls in, I don't think we were responsible for S&M styles, perhaps.
Jim Morrison got the idea for leather pants from Gerard Malanga.
We were the first to do any of that kind of stuff.
But weirdo dressing was, that's rock and roll to the roots.
Screamin' Jay Hawkins in his leopard suits.
Big Bopper, the first time I saw him was wearing a leopard skin suit.
I said, what the hell is that?
They said, it's a big bopper.
I said, oh.
That makes it OK. Oh, yeah.
We never set out to be a fashion influence.
We didn't try and dream up our own equivalent of beetle suits.
Okay, this should wind it up.
What do you think, why has the band, why have you broke up and gone your separate ways?
You said you got tired of living that hostile analysis.
Well, I would have gotten tired of it eventually.
Just squabbles, I would say, kind of wore us down.
Just speculating on that in the biography.
It's hard to say.
See, Lou more or less, well, Lou forced John out, which I didn't like.
So I stewed on that for a good while.
And I was pretty, I stuck it to Lou whenever I got a chance on account of that.
And then Lou eventually left under pressures and
shifting times, a shifting decade.
Lou was a little put out, I would say, in 1970.
So I stayed playing after Lou left, but I was always looking around to see where I'd go in graduate school.
So I just sent out a few applications.
I had all the numbers and stuff, so I knew I'd get in.
I figured I'd get some support.
I was right.
But after Lou left, he tried to talk me into doing a thing with him.
Just me and you.
We'll go to Europe and put together a whole new thing.
We'll be far away from these poisonous idiots who are bothering us all the time.
It's very nice to have a scene that, we'll say, reveres you.
loves you or something like that.
Well, you are surrounded by people you've known a long time and very close to, socially.
It has this negative corollary that they feel close enough to you in everything you do to complain long and bitterly about everything that you do.
They don't think you ought to be doing it.
We hear all these harangues about what we ought to be doing.
Why weren't we?
You know, people looking out for your own best interests.
You hear enough of this stuff.
After a while, you figure, what is happening?
You know, on our case, we're not bothering anybody.
So Luthor, perhaps we ought to just go to Europe and hide out.
Do like we did before.
If Lou John and I go into a room for two weeks, something's going to come out at the end of it.
A whole lot.
We always knew that.
We could turn on material instantly.
Tons of our stuff had never even recorded.
We'd practice it, and then once we had it down, we lost interest.
And then the things that are really a challenge, let's see if we can make this work.
Remember what we were trying to do the other night?
Let's see if we can get that to be something.
So then we go do that with great energy and forget all the things that we rehearsed that we're supposed to be recording.
That's good and it's bad.
Recorded pieces often don't sound really polished.
That's good and it's bad.
But it does have the benefit of, let's say, sincere energy.
It is fresh and you have some desire.
Like that Rolling Stones thing, it's only rock and roll, but I like it.
The way that sounds sounded to me like they must have hashed that out the way we used to.
There's so much more that it needs or could have.
That could have been a really slick, major Rolling Stone effort.
But it wasn't.
They were content to leave it as it was.
I like it fine.
It's only rock and roll, but I like it.
And that's all.
The way the song is reflects exactly what it's talking about.
Is it rock and roll?
Yeah.
Well, that's good enough.
That's all this is.
I like it.
You think it ought to have horns.
You think it ought to have a better bass part.
You think it ought to have a guitar solo.
Too bad, it doesn't.
Still, rock and roll, this is all you get.
And we always avoided the gratuitous guitar fill.
I always hate guitar fills.
I like them.
I think they're great.
One, appropriate.
But every time the singer stops, isn't the signal for the guitar player to start flapping?
So we avoided that pretty much.
You know, it's all our songs.
That's a tendency picked up by the new wavers.
They avoid the fills religiously.
It's nice to have a little running riff.
Oh, it's nice to throw a fill in here and there.
But that sounds too much like the electric blues freaks who were running wild in the 60s, too.
I contended that the blues revival was over because they played all the notes.
There were no notes left in any combination that hadn't been played.
The entire permutation had been strung out.
It was impossible to play two musical phrases that hadn't been played by somebody sometime or other.
I said, therefore, give it up.
I have to find something else.
John Carroll playing blues, when he first came over from England, that would have been terrific.
He didn't know any blues works.
The Welshman Sings the Blues.
That would appeal to me.
The Welsh academician sings the blues.
Sings American Negro blues.
That would have been a great album.
That would have astounded everybody.
I can't imagine what it would have been.
But you know what I mean.
If you can't avoid cliches no matter how hard you try, then you really ought to
I ride a different horse and mix my metaphors.
Who wants to play electric blues?
All I can do is play it as well as Johnny Winter did it last week.
Maybe not as well, but better.
Just, oh yeah, yeah, that's clearly influenced by it.
It's impossible to be totally original.
You don't have to be totally derivative either.
A good blues band was Siegel Schwal.
Chicago guys, white.
religious blues purists.
Sound good.
Kind of like early Butterfield, but even more rooted, shall I say.
You know what I say about that?
Is this thing picking up anything?
It should be.
I think it's over.
I don't know.
I have a way of swallowing my words.
Okay.
Okay, finis.
That's it.
Now we can go over to the union.
